body:
@cheddar : Higher question overall.

But from a conceptual standpoint null and empty are distinct ideas. I get a bit nervous throwing null around as a valid value because it's confusing if it means "error" or "empty", and throwing nulls around on purpose is an easy way to accidentally NPE somewhere. Lots of other druid code uses empty sets instead of null, and I was wondering if you have a compelling through on why things should map to null instead of to an empty object.

Additionally, as per the SQL example mentioned previously, it helps if we have just one representation that is not confusing to folks coming from other data stores.

@res-life Just to be clear, is the error around the result
{
"version" : "v1",
"timestamp" : "2015-01-06T05:37:00.000Z",
"event" : {
"clicks" : 28
}

showing up initially and then disappearing later on in the query?

{
"event" : {
   //  not have sub5 dimension. All the sub5 value in Kafka Msg is not empty. 
"clicks" : 28
}

The query is same, but the result is different. At first have null sub5 dimension when ingesting, later on this result is:
{
"clicks" : 3,
"sub5" : "BB1"
}

@fjy seems not the same problem.
I specified the regexp filter:
      "filter": {
           "type": "regex",
            "dimension": "sub5",
            "pattern": "B"
       }
but result is:
      "event" : {
             // not have sub5 dimension. All the sub5 value in Kafka Msg is not empty. 
             "clicks" : 28
        }
it's not functional issue but performance issue. Only occurs under high throughput ingesting.

A potential fix is to ensure that all `DruidModule`s and `CliCommandCreator`s implement the following or similar:

```
  @Override
  public int hashCode(){
    return getClass().getCanonicalName().hashCode();
  }
```

Implementing a simple `equals` method is highly suggested as well.
